0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">“</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">the further y</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">ou are from towns, services, jobs and friends, the more important transport becomes. That's why rural Britain needs good transport just as much as urban Britain. In fact it always has...So if you accept that we need good transport to live our lives and exp</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">and our economy then two questions come to mind. How do you provide it so that rural people can benefit too? And how can you make sure the beauty of Britain doesn't suffer?</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">”</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">How do Government and local authorities identify demand for passenger transport in</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold"> isolated communities (including rural and urban areas and island communities)?</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">It is difficult to answer this question without also considering Network Rail, co</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">mmercial bus and train operating companies</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">recently created </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">Local Transport Boards.</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> The bro</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">ad range of bodies responsible highlights how fractured responsibility is and, in many instances, the transport needs of isolated communities are not picked up well.</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> Although </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">a duty to co-operate between planning bodies</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> was created by the Localism Act 2011</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">, this duty does not extend to </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">all transport </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">bodies</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">This is not such a problem in major urban areas where there have been Passenger Transport Authorities that take the lead on transport planning, other than perhaps for bus networks that are privately op</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">erated. Integration can be a particular problem in rural areas, particularly where travel needs fall across county boundaries. L</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">ocal Transport Plans in theory should </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">assess the needs and provide proposals for all areas. In practice they often consist of hi</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">gh level principles and delivery plans for the main towns in an area. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">Perhaps the best examples of an exception to this problem are the Local Area Travel Plans drawn up as part of Central</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> Bedfordshire</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> Council’s Local Transport Plan. These cover groups of </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">villages and besides setting out means to improve bus and cycle routes, for example, they are integrated into land use plans. Not only does this mean that </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">transport networks can be planned around changes to demand from future developments, there can also b</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">e developer funding to help secure these changes.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">In relation to the private sector, operators that receive public funding should, as a condition of that funding be required to co-operate in the planning of their timetables and ticketing.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">Network Rail consulted this summer on a Long Term Planning Process that </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">considers the needs of the railways over a 30 year planning horizon. While supportive of this process, CPRE raised concerns that none of the five market studies gave proper considerati</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">on to the needs of rural areas. The ‘Regional Urban Passenger’ study was the only study to consider local rail services and then only focused on commuter travel to major urban areas. </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">In many cases </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">improvements to more profitable long distance services has </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">been made at the cost to local stopping services so CPRE believes that the rail needs of rural communities should have been considered from the start of the process.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">T</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">he newest transport bodies are Local Transport Boards (LTBs), which have been set up in t</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">he last year to prioritise and oversee the delivery of major local transport schemes. Many large transport schemes suck up other sources of funding, such as Community Infrastructure Levy, developer planning contributions and New Homes Bonus, that could be </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">used for improving public transport. Local authorities are now liable for major scheme cost overruns, following recent rule changes and there are already examples, for example the Bexhill Hastings Link Road and South Devon Link Roads, where local public tr</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">ansport budgets have been raided to pay for road-building. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; list-style-position:inside; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">With Local Enterprise Partnerships having a significant role in LTBs, there are concerns that this may happen more in future. Certainly very little consideration appears to be given to the needs o</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">f isolated and rural communities by LTBs</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> or potential impacts of schemes on them</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">CPRE is carrying out </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">research </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">jointly </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">with </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">the Campaign for Better Transport about how different LTBs have been </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">engaging the public and </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">prioritising their areas differently a</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">nd will forward a copy of the final report to the Committee. Initial findings suggest that there has been a great</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">deal of variation, with some LTBs working very well and other very badly</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">To what extent are the needs of different groups of passengers (e.g.</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold"> people with disabilities, older people, young people) taken into account in determining the provision of public transport to isolated communities?</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; list-style-position:inside; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">The </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">Equality Act 2010 requires consideration of the impact on groups of people with protected characteristics, such as age, disability and race, such as through Equality Impact Assessments. There are two shortcomings with the law as it stands. First, it genera</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">lly relates to process rather than substantive outcomes. In other words, so long as the impacts have been properly considered, funding and policy decisions that disadvantage certain groups can be made. The second is this leaves out other less defined group</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">s, such as people living in rural areas </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">(although there are separate rural impact assessments) </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">or those without access to cars.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; list-style-position:inside; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><a href="http://www.cprewm.org.uk/ruraltransport.htm"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Research</span><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline"> by CPRE West Midlands </span><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">R</span><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">egion</span><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">al </span><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">G</span><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">roup in 2009</span></a><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">suggested that</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> although 90% of rural households had a car, at any one time fewer than half of people in rural areas had access to a car, for example where the breadwinner had taken it to work. A further </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">issue is that many rural households can barely afford to keep a car</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> but have no other realistic choice, so have to scrimp on other essential spending, such as heating.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; list-style-position:inside; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">Some newer forms of demand responsive transport are only available for those who meet certain criteria</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> and are scheduled for travel from villages into town</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">s and back again</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">. Where there replace scheduled routes that are open to all, this can have indirect impacts on a wide range of people.</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> For example, people living in towns without cars can be unable to use these services to access work in rural areas or to </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">walk in the countryside at the weekend.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; list-style-position:inside; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">A further problem is that decisions about the location of services often fail to consider the needs of people to reach them. It may be cheaper, for example to build a new health centre on the edge of a town away from</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> a bus stop. But the long term costs of providing extra transport and missed appointments quickly add up. Accessibility planning helps change this but, since it was promoted in 2003 by the Department for Transport (DfT), it has fallen by the way side.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">What</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold"> are the main challenges associated with providing better and more consistent bus and rail services to isolated communities? How can these challenges be overcome?</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; list-style-position:inside; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">There can be a </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">‘</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">c</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">hicken and egg</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">’</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> situation </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">where unless there is a critical mass of services </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">in place for a few years, there will not be a critical mass of </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">regular passenger</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">s to pay the way for them. A number of funding streams have been short-term and have ended before people have become used to using them. Unless rural transport is put on a long</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> term footing, people are unlikely to want to rely on it because bus timetables can, for example, be changed with just a few weeks’ notice.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; list-style-position:inside; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">Community Rail Partnerships have produced impressive growth in passenger numbers to rural railways that were </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">serious</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">ly at risk of closure only a decade or two ago. </span><a href="http://www.cpre.org.uk/magazine/opinion/item/3139-an-integrated-network-can-revive-rural-transport"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Responding to the Secretary of State for Transport’s speech</span></a><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> to CPRE</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">, Prof Paul Salveson MBE, </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">creator of the concept of community rail, suggested applying similar principles to rural bus services.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; list-style-position:inside; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">Providing services for t</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">he last or first leg of a journey is vital but is often particularly challenging</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> due to a lack of demand to make regular services</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> viable without extensive subsidy. While some users, particularly those who are less ambulant, will need some form of subsidised transport, for others a range of options should be facilitated</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">, including car sharing as part of a combined mobility agenda</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">. Wh</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">ile in the UK, rural cycling makes up 2% of journeys, a proportion as low as in urban areas, Germany is aiming to increase cycling from 8 to 13% of rural travel.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; list-style-position:inside; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">According to 2012 DfT statistics on accessibility, </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">79% of England’s population </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">outside of Lond</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">on</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> is within 400m of the public transport network and 92%</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">is within 800m. For rural</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> areas, the figures are 36% and 71% respectively. </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">Providing safe access</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> to stops and stations is crucial. This can be a challenge in rural areas as</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> rural roads</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> rarely have </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">a</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> footway or cycleway</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">, meaning</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> people cycling or walking have to share the carriageway with drivers travelling close to motorway speeds.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; list-style-position:inside; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">Creating rural transport hubs, which have regular services to the wider transport network but that are accessible by</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> a range of different means of transport ac</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">ross a wider rural area can play a role</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">The new neighbourhood tier of planning is particularly suited to improving the last and first leg of travel because local people will be most </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">aware of the difficulties. Unf</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">ortunately the DfT has not engaged in it, while the Department for Communities and Local Government’s new Planning Practice Guidance on neighbourhood planning ignores transport. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; list-style-position:inside; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">CPRE’s innovative </span><a href="http://transporttoolkit.org.uk/"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Transport T</span><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">ool</span><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">kit</span></a><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">, which was launched in April 2013, </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">covers these issues and </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">sets out a range of ideas</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> for parish councils, neighbourhoods and community groups</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">, including car sharing</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> electric bike pools</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> and parish travel plans</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">How effectively do Community Transpor</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">t services address the needs of passengers in isolated communities? How could Community Transport be improved?</span></p><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; list-style-position:inside; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">Community Transport (CT) has two particular roles. Because of lower operating costs, it c</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">an be excellent filler of gap</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">s in the public transport n</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">etwork, whether spatially (isolated and rural areas) or temporally (evening and weekend services).</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">It can also offer a social service for those with particular mobility or other health needs, who could not use normal public transport. These two forms of CT should be distinguished better as they fulfil different needs. The higher level of social contact </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">can be important in the latter type but people, for example teenagers, might be put off using CT if it is thought to be something for old people. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; list-style-position:inside; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">The first form of CT needs to be better integrated into the public transport network, so that it is seen as a</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">n integral part of it. Continental transport planning highlights the need for one network, one map, one ticket and this is how demand responsive transport (DRT) works in Switzerland. The smart ticketing pilot in Norfolk should provide useful lessons for th</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">e rest of the country. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">To what extent should passengers in isolated communities be expected to rely on taxis and other demand-responsive transport services?</span></p><ol start="22" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; list-style-position:inside; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">People in isolated communities should not be expected to rely on taxis because these can be unaffordable. As noted above, shared taxis and other forms of DRT will often be the only practical way to provide services where demand is low. It is likely to be m</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">ore efficient </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">to have feeder </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">services from isolated communities to the nearest stop on a regular public transport service, rather than expect to take the same vehicle all the way into town.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">What are the main challenges associated with funding transport se</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">rvices in isolated communities? How can these services be made more affordable?</span></p><ol start="23" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; list-style-position:inside; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">Changes to Bus Subsidy Operating Grant that give local authorities greater control should help enable cross-subsidisation of lightly used routes by more commercial ones. A thre</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">at is the removal of ring-fencing for this funding after 2016.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; list-style-position:inside; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">As noted above, ensuring long-term security of services is crucial if they are to be used. If public transport services are not competitive compared to car travel – in terms of cost, journey ti</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">me, comfort, convenience etc. - then they will only attract a small proportion of potential passengers. This means that a wide range of other decisions can affect the viability of services. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; list-style-position:inside; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">Research by CPRE in the 1990s showed that Park &amp; Ride services ex</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">tract passengers from local bus services and this effect is likely to be greater now as such services compete for dwindling bus subsidy with local services that link villages to towns. Providing </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">extra</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> free car parking in a town centre or station may damage</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> the viability of </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">local bus services </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">which in turn can</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> then mean even more pressure on car parking</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> and greater congestion</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">. Damaging the viability of high street may mean people turn to out of town supermarkets, that are harder to serve well by public trans</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">port</span></li><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; list-style-position:inside; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">These competing factors highlight the need for an integrated approach to transport planning, based on co-operation, whether of neighbouring towns or bus and rail. This is at the core of </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">the approach in </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">CPRE’s </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">T</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">ransport </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">T</span><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">oolkit.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">September 2013</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> Bodies included are highway authorities and Integrated Transport Authorities but not Network Rail, operators or Local Transport Boards. </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">See regulation 4 of </span><a href="http://www.legislation.gov.uk/uksi/2012/767/regulation/4/made"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">The Town and Country Planning (Local Planning) (England) Regulations 2012</span></a><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">.</span></p></body></html>